# LEC-19: Database Scaling Patterns

*(Step-by-step scaling — a case study)*

## What Will You Learn?
- Step-by-step manner, when to choose which scaling option.
- Which scaling option is feasible **practically** at the moment (i.e., scale incrementally, don't over-engineer upfront).

## A Case Study: Cab Booking App

**Starting point:**
- Tiny startup.
- ~10 customers onboard.
- A **single small-machine DB** stores all customers, trips, locations, booking data, and customer trip history.
- ~1 trip booking every 5 minutes.

## Your App Becoming Famous, But… (The Problem Begins)
- Requests scale up to **30 bookings per minute**.
- The tiny DB system has started **performing poorly**.
- **API latency** has increased a lot.
- Transactions facing **Deadlock, Starvation, and frequent failure**.
- **Sluggish** app experience.
- **Customer dis-satisfaction.**

## Is There Any Solution?
- We have to apply some kind of **performance optimisation** measures.
- We might have to **scale** our system going forward.

---

## Pattern 1 — Query Optimisation & Connection Pool Implementation
- **Cache** frequently used non-dynamic data, like booking history, payment history, user profiles, etc.
- Introduce **Database Redundancy** (or maybe use NoSQL).
- Use **connection pool libraries** to **cache DB connections**.
- Multiple application threads can use the **same DB connection**.
- **Good optimisation** as of now.
- **Result:** Scaled the business to one more city, and now getting ~**100 bookings per minute**.

> **Extra:** A connection pool avoids the expensive overhead of opening/closing a new DB connection for every single request — connections are reused from a pre-established pool, which is one of the cheapest, highest-impact optimisations you can make before touching your architecture at all.

## Pattern 2 — Vertical Scaling or Scale-up
- Upgrading the initial tiny machine.
- E.g., RAM by 2x and SSD by 3x, etc.
- Scale-up is **pocket-friendly only till a point**.
- The more you scale up, **cost increases exponentially**.
- **Good optimisation** as of now.
- **Result:** Business grows further — scaled to 3 more cities, now getting **300 bookings per minute**.

## Pattern 3 — Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS)
- The scaled-up big machine is **not able to handle** all read/write requests.
- **Separate read/write operations** physical-machine-wise.
- **2 more machines** added as **replicas** to the primary machine.
- **All read queries → replicas.**
- **All write queries → primary.**
- **Result:** Business grows to 2 more cities.
- **New problem:** Primary is **not able to handle all write requests**; **lag** between primary and replica is impacting user experience.

> **Extra:** This is essentially the **Master-Slave** replication pattern (covered in detail in LEC-21) — CQRS as a broader architectural principle separates the "command" (write) responsibility from the "query" (read) responsibility, which naturally maps to routing writes to a primary and reads to replicas.

## Pattern 4 — Multi Primary Replication
- **Why not distribute write requests to replicas also?**
- **All machines** can work as **primary & replica** simultaneously.
- Multi-primary configuration is organised as a **logical circular ring**.
- **Write data to any node.**
- **Read data from any node** that replies to the broadcast first.
- **Result:** Scaled to 5 more cities — but the system is **in pain again** (~50 req/s can't be handled well).

## Pattern 5 — Partitioning of Data by Functionality
- What about **separating the location tables** into a separate DB schema?
- What about putting that DB in **separate machines** with primary-replica or multi-primary configuration?
- **Different DBs can host data categorised by different functionality** (e.g., one DB/cluster for locations, another for bookings, another for payments).
- **Backend/application layer** has to take responsibility to **join the results** (since data now lives in different DBs, joins can't happen at the DB level anymore).
- **Result:** Planning to expand the business to other countries.

> **Extra:** This is essentially applying **Vertical Partitioning at the database/service level**, similar in spirit to what modern **microservices architectures** do — each service/domain (Location, Booking, Payment) gets its own database, and the application layer stitches results together instead of relying on cross-domain SQL joins.

## Pattern 6 — Horizontal Scaling or Scale-out
- **Sharding** — multiple shards.
- Allocate **50 machines** — all having the same DB schema — each machine just holds a **part of the data**.
- **Locality of data** should be maintained (related data stored together on the same shard where possible).
- Each machine can have its **own replicas**, which may be used in failure recovery.
- **Sharding is generally hard to apply. But "No Pain, No Gain."**
- **Result:** Scaling the business **across continents**.

## Pattern 7 — Data Centre Wise Partition
- Requests travelling **across continents** are experiencing **high latency**.
- What about **distributing traffic across data centres**?
- **Data centres across continents.**
- Enable **cross data centre replication**, which helps with **disaster recovery**.
- This always **maintains Availability** of the system.
- **Result:** Now, plan for an **IPO** 🙂

---

## Summary Table — Progression of Scaling Patterns

| Pattern | Technique | Solves | Introduces New Problem |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Query Optimisation & Connection Pooling | Slow queries, connection overhead | Only delays the inevitable — still single DB |
| 2 | Vertical Scaling (Scale-up) | Insufficient hardware capacity | Cost grows exponentially with scale |
| 3 | CQRS (Read Replicas) | Single machine can't handle read+write together | Primary still bottlenecked on writes; replication lag |
| 4 | Multi-Primary Replication | Distributes write load too | Conflict resolution complexity; still hits scaling ceiling |
| 5 | Partitioning by Functionality | Different domains overload each other | App layer must now handle joins manually |
| 6 | Horizontal Scaling / Sharding | Any single DB's storage/throughput limit | High complexity; re-sharding; poor for analytics |
| 7 | Data Centre Wise Partition | Cross-continent latency | Requires robust cross-DC replication & consistency handling |

> **Extra — Key takeaway for interviews:** This case study demonstrates the **general philosophy of database scaling**: always start with the *cheapest, simplest* optimisation (query tuning, connection pooling) before jumping to more complex, expensive, and operationally heavy solutions (vertical scaling → read replicas → multi-primary → functional partitioning → sharding → geo-distribution). Each step solves the immediate bottleneck but introduces new complexity, so scaling is an **incremental, problem-driven process**, not something you over-engineer for on day one.

